Harry Potter's Literary Magic
Princeton — — This summer, at literary festivals and bookstores around the world, readers celebrated the 20th anniversary of J·K·Rowling's first Harry Potter novel — —  Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (renamed in the United States as Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone). They had a good reason to celebrate.
Since this young wizard first appeared on June 26, 1997, this "boy who lived" has become a "symbol of resilience and perseverance."
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, has been translated into more than 70 languages, and has sold a total of 450 million copies.
The eight movies based on this book have earned a total of $7 billion, while Harry Potter theme toys and merchandise have generated another $7 billion in revenue.
It's hard for people of specific age and with a literary mind to imagine a day when the global audience wasn't captivated by Rowling's works.
Therefore, I'm often astonished by my students' poor reactions to "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" in the fall of 1999, when I first included the novel in my popular literature course at Princeton University. I have been teaching the "best-selling American books" series since 1993.
The course studies popular works from the 17th century to the present and invites students to ponder why and how these bestsellers attracted their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask students to choose a final work that represents the popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, the Potions master attacked the American coast fiercely.
In June, the American publisher of this series of works hastily put the deluxe edition of the second book in the Harry Potter series, "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets", into bookstores.
The institution also published the third book in this series, "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban", and the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone", on September 8th.
By the end of the month, Rowling's novel had swept up the top three positions on The New York Times bestselling fiction list, while the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" sat atop the paperback bestseller list.
Time magazine even put this bespectacled wizard on the cover.
Wherever the eye may fall, Harry Potter's image is ubiquitous.
My students are eager to know why such a frenzy has occurred.
Good grief, they were thoroughly disappointed.
In their view, the Harry Potter series is nothing but trashy nonsense, far inferior to the beloved series of their childhood, such as The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings, when compared.
Although they have only just passed through their childhood a few years ago, they have already begun to criticize Harry Potter like many notorious adult critics, saying it is "made-up", "poor writing", "clichés", and "tedious".

They see no miracles, no wit, and no warmth in Harry.
The students' disgust surprises me, but looking back, there really wasn't anything to make a big deal about.
Although adults made up a large part of the audience for the Harry Potter series from the beginning, these students were precisely at an age where they could not objectively recognize the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They are too old to accept new children's books, but they are still too young to have their own children (at the time I had just had my own child), and they are anxiously convinced that although Harry's series is very popular now, it will be soon forgotten by people.
Second year autumn, that is 2000, the next batch of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" as their end-of-term analytical work, like their peers before them, they confidently refused to accept this book.
Let's fast forward to the spring of 2007.
After putting the course on hold for a few years, I taught "Best Sellers in America" again.
When students chose their end-of-term analytical work, they chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone".
And I was preparing to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments are extremely positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who were not university students when they first read the works of Rowling, but rather teenagers in their early teens, just entering adolescence. This means that they grew up with Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
Similarly, the same thing happened in autumn 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto, not a label.
Will Harry disappear from memory?
As long as we are still alive, it is impossible.
I taught a bestseller course twice since 2010, and both times, the students chose to write the final review based on non-Harry Potter novels.
Are they tired of Harry?
From the comments I received in my other course, "Children's Literature," on the Harry series, this seems unlikely.
Now, I choose to put one of the Harry Potter novels into the curriculum, but I did not choose 'Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone.' Instead, I chose 'Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban'  —  This is my favorite Harry Potter novel, it marks a transition from children's literature to young adult novels in the series, with complex descriptions of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and mercy.
My many students also like this book the most.
How long can the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach children's literature, I have to conduct a survey first : "Which books on the outline have you read in your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban".
In 2012, this number rose to 94%.
But the years that followed, the percentage continued to decline—87% in 2014, and decreased to 81% in 2016.
These are not scientific, I know.
But I am curious: next spring when I teach "Children's Literature" again, will the percentage of those who have read Harry Potter drop below 80%?
Will facts prove that the students of 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status is constantly declining and will never become an eternal classic?
Or is there a tipping point ahead, where the percentage can stabilize and not decline further?
Perhaps Harry's 40th-anniversary could tell us the answer.
Until then, I was happy to have him invited into my classroom.
